{"key":"post-16228034","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>16228034</id>\n<content>&lt;/font&gt;&lt;blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;small&quot;&gt;Quote:&lt;/font&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The theory behind this is that by cutting the agar up you increase ur inoculation points by 30 fold&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&lt;font class=&quot;post&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Unfortunately, it doesn't work that way.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When you shake the agar around in the jar, the bits of mycelium on both sides are not going to fall off and start growing.&amp;nbsp; After the shake, the only spots you'll see growing are from the agar wedges themselves.&amp;nbsp; The mycelium needs this agar to be able to jump off into the grains.&amp;nbsp; Also, transferred mycelium grows very slowly until it gets established into the new medium.&amp;nbsp; Then, it picks up speed and finishes colonizing.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;It's similar with grain to grain transfers.&amp;nbsp; If you use a 1:10 spawn rate, the jar or bag will be fully colonized in about ten days.&amp;nbsp; If you use a 1:5 spawn rate, you'll only reduce that by one day or less, not cut it in half.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>16228067</next>\n<prev>16228001</prev>\n<first>16225524</first>\n<last>16228867</last>\n<when>1337003560</when>\n<utime>05/14/12 04:52 PM</utime>\n</post>"}